The most brutal sport on Earth? . . . Dating back over 500 years the Calcio Storico ("historic football") is an early form of football and rugby and remains one of the best-known and most violent Italian traditions. The annual tournament is competed between four teams, Bianchi, Rossi, Verdi and Blu, representing the neighborhoods of Florence, and is still played in the same Florentine Piazza it is thought to have started in. This brutal combination of rugby, football, and wrestling has few rules, fighting is allowed but kicks to the head are forbidden. A match lasts 50 minutes, and the playing field is a giant sand pit with a narrow slit constituting the 'goal' running the width of each end. The eventual winners are honoured with a cow | June 16, 2019 | : @antoniomasiello @calciostoricofiorentino

I dont need to walk to live. - @the_mighty_quinn21 Photographer @patricksmithphotos shares the stories behind his powerful pictures of wheelchair bodybuilder Johnny Quinn: For Johnny Quinn, one of his strongest relationships is with his long time trainer Robert Caltabiano. Learning to handle Quinns fierce athleticism and disability was something Caltabiano had never been challenged with before the two met. Without core muscle function, training is vigorous, intense and often non-traditional for Quinn and the two are said theyre proud of the obstacles theyve overcame together. These two are both professionals, as well as IFBB pro athletes, and have an infectious brotherly connection. There is a story just between these two and I learned a lot about life while photographing them both. However, finding compelling, telling images in the same small environment was a major challenge. This is one of my favorite images that shows creativity can always be incorporated in storytelling. [Post 4 of 4]

I dont need to walk to live. - @the_mighty_quinn21 Photographer @patricksmithphotos shares the stories behind his powerful pictures of wheelchair bodybuilder Johnny Quinn: Backstage at any sporting event is always compelling to photographers. Its an environment many fans never get to see. This scene was no different as Johnny Quinn was bronzed by coach and posing coach Jerry 'Doc' Wheeler prior to a guest posing at an event. Each athlete in Quinns division has a visible disability to fans and judges alike - theyre in a wheelchair. But compare Quinn to anyone else in the pump up room and hes no different - and if not - larger and more defined muscularly. This moment helps show viewers that despite Quinns visible difference, among the controlled chaos in the room, he would have no problem competing against any other athlete. [Post 3 of 4]

I dont need to walk to live. - @the_mighty_quinn21 Photographer @patricksmithphotos shares the stories behind his powerful pictures of wheelchair bodybuilder Johnny Quinn: After a training session in April, I asked Johnny Quinn if I could document his home life for the first time. Early in our time together, I was more focused on making Quinn comfortable as we talked to get to know one another. During that moment, I missed a moment of him acknowledging a neighbor who drove by on a motorcycle. To me, it was a moment that would help show he was unfazed by motorcycles - one thing that contributed to his disability. I was mentally beating myself up over missing the moment. Little did I know, sometimes you get a second chance at a photo without ever thinking you get one. As we navigated back to his house after taking his dog to the bathroom, the motorcycle was now parked, and he made his way by it. A simple moment to many, this image communicates that he survived a horrific accident, and formed a new identity in the process, and isnt haunted by a past experience. [Post 2 of 4]

I dont need to walk to live. - @the_mighty_quinn21 Photographer @patricksmithphotos shares the stories behind his powerful pictures of wheelchair bodybuilder Johnny Quinn: When I found out Quinn was asked to guest pose - otherwise known as performing an entertaining routine rather than compete - during the 68th NPC Lehigh Valley Championships in Allentown, PA - I knew it would be an important picture. I decided to take a risk and setup a remote camera behind the stage under backdrop curtain. His routine was very energetic and also inspiring to many - as he was told so by fans afterward. It was also the first time I documented Quinn on stage in which I felt the same emotions as the audience. This image communicates what we all felt. The combination of: one of his signature moves, the dramatic light, and his playful Joker style mask, all helped it be one of the most powerful images of the story. [Post 1 of 4]

@gettyimages Getty Images photographer Richard Heathcote is taking over @gettyimages today for a closer look at some of his favourite pictures. To see more of his work check out his Instagram @rheathcote __ During London 2012 we started experimenting with robotically controlled cameras. Due to the nature of the venue roofs we couldnt put photographers in positions we previously would have, so we mounted cameras we could control via laptop. I wanted to get simple, strong, graphic images that were pleasing to look at. For the Judo there was an Olympic rings logo between the two mats so I framed up the camera with the logo very predominant and waited for some action to happen underneath. When this judoka won his bout he laid back in exhaustion spreading out, the image looks like a flag with the four very simple contrasting colours. rheathcote | August 2, 2012 [3 of 3]

@gettyimages Getty Images photographer Richard Heathcote is taking over @gettyimages today for a closer look at some of his pictures. To see more of his work check out his Instagram @rheathcote __ This image is all about patience, timing and a touch of luck. I saw the umbrella logo, synonymous with the late Arnold Palmer, earlier in the week and wanted to get a player walking past as it was such a strong shape. I must have been there several times when caddies walked up blocking the logo or other people inside the ropes stood in front of it. Then late one day a couple of players waited back on the tee box as everyone else walked forward. I knew this was my chance to get it clean, then Martin Kaymer started gesturing and swinging his arms. I waited and when they entered the frame I got the image here where it gives the optical illusion that he is holding the umbrella. @rheathcote | March 17, 2017 [2 of 3]

While the crews were in full flow mid race something appeared in the water in the distance. @worldpressphoto Serena Williams of the USA celebrates winning a point during her fourth round match against Jelena Jankovic of Serbia on day seven of the Australian Open 2007 at Melbourne Park on January 21, 2007 in Melbourne, Australia. My name is Cameron Spencer (@cjspencois) and Im a staff photographer with Getty Images based in Sydney, Australia. I specialise in photographing sport and this week I'm taking over the World Press Photo Foundation Instagram feed and I'll be sharing some of my favourite work with you. My passion is capturing defining moments in sport from a unique perspective. I will talk through the background of these images as I post in the coming days. Serena Williams is my favourite athlete in the world to photograph. Williams has dominated Womens tennis for the past decade, the best female player in the modern era and on court she is so dynamic and athletic. As a photographer you can always expect the unexpected and it is always a buzz documenting her playing as she wears her heart on her sleeve and plays with such emotion. Whether it is a baseline stretch or capturing a winning scream, the results are breathtaking moments frozen in time @serenawilliams

@gettyimages Roger Bannister was the first man to run the mile in under 4 minutes, clocking in at 3 minutes and 59.4 seconds in 1954. Norman Potter was the only person to photograph that historic moment. _ Using a glass plate camera, Potter captured Bannister with one shot. The photograph was wired around the world and appeared in countless publications. It remains to this day a key moment in the history of both sports and press photography. @gettyimages Getty Images photographer Patrick Smith is taking over @gettyimages today for a closer look at some of his images. To see more of his work check out his Instagram @patricksmithphotos __ One of the many things that draws us to photojournalism is that you never know what can happen. Many of us Getty Images staff photographers have the amazing opportunity to travel the globe to document the world's biggest games, yet when we're back home, we document our local teams. These games can often feel repetitious because we spend so much time in the same venues. But I always know that I may document something new, fresh that will make our viewers either feel an emotion or be amazed by the beauty that sports often showcases. Transmitting pictures in the work room with no outside view - a small television keeps us photographers up to date in the game. When I saw a rainbow appear on said TV, I sprinted to the concourse with the widest lens I had. Time seemed to stop as I photographed as many angles as I could. Before I knew it, the rainbow vanished and I was left with a moment that will never be forgotten by a nearly packed Camden Yards. - @patricksmithphotos | June 28, 2013

@gettyimages Getty Images photographer Patrick Smith is taking over @gettyimages today for a closer look at some of his images. To see more of his work check out his Instagram @patricksmithphotos __ Every sports photographer wants to capture the big hit or the game-changing goal. While we never want anyone to get hurt, it's often the miscues or incidents on the field that make a compelling image. This motorsports accident happened to occur at 2:47AM, after a long weather delay in the Daytona Coke Zero 400. With my eyes heavy, and wanting to sleep, the race finished in front of us all, but a few cars back Austin Dillon was airborne going into the fence at 200mph. Instinctively panning backwards with my lens, years of training came organically which helped capture this image, at only 1/640 of a second. To this day I have yet to see anything so unspeakable. - @patricksmithphotos | July 6, 2015

@gettyimages Cycling fans had quietly muttered that perhaps this years Tour de France was proving too easy, despite some dramatic crashes, controversial decisions and a tough weekend in the Jura mountains in the first week. The second week seemed only to contain leisurely flat ride outs followed by sprint finishes. Thursday's Stage 12 however saw the peloton arrive in the Pyrenees with a particularly tough finish in Peyragudes. Towards the end of each stage, our photographers alternate between being on the motorbike following and being at finish line. For this mountain stage our photographer Chris Graythen (@chgphoto) was at the finish, and by positioning himself low he managed to capture the brutal nature of the final ramp up to the line, with French favourite @romainbardet being urged on to stage victory by the home crowd. @gettyimagesgallery Ezra Shaw: "This picture was taken at the in 2015. I had heard about this mountain bike competition for years before I got the opportunity to go out to photograph it. The Rampage is an invite-only, free ride competition held just outside of Utah's Zion National Park. All the riders start at the same spot on top of the canyon, but they can pick their own line down the mountain - each line is even crazier than the next one. I was scared to hike up some parts of the canyon, so I can't even imagine riding down it. I was out there for a few days, so I was able to figure out which riders would choose which part of the mountain. For this shot, I knew that Sam Reynolds was going to go big off of a jump so I positioned myself in a spot where I could show the vastness of the landscape and incorporate his amazing skills. The "Superman Jump" soaring over three canyon gap in this picture won the best trick award." - @eoshaw | October, 2015 Visit @gettyimagesgallery for more of the 'Visions of Sport 2017' exhibition.

@gettyimages A lot of timing and work went into making this image and thats one of the reasons I love it so much. It was a story about surfing in Alaska and in particular one wave, the Bore Tide, that comes in only 2 times a day. And the wave only happens a few times a year making it a destination for extreme surfing. Surfers show up early in the morning and late in the afternoon to get into position and wait for the wave to come crashing in. This image was taken on the second to last day of my shoot and I had found this spot thanks to the local surfers that showed me where I could walk out on to the mudflats. It is a very dangerous area and you can only walk out so far and then the mud turns to quicksand. I woke up at about 3am to get all the way out to the position and wait for the wave. As I was standing out in the middle of Turnagain Arm I saw these two surfers walking out into position. The mood and blue hue of the photo was due to the ever changing Alaskan weather.I think the greatest part of this image is that it shows the vastness of the Alaskan wilderness and how humans are never afraid to challenge life in the name of a sport they love. - @streeterlecka | July 14, 2014 Sport2017: Photographer Favourites is a new exhibition @gettyimagesgallery in London which includes intimate scenes of world-class athletes and remarkable moments of human endeavour. @gettyimages "Whilst this is not technically an action shot as it focuses on two competitors shortly before a race start, it is still one of my favorite sailing pictures. It was taken during the London 2012 Games off the coast of Weymouth and Portland which hosted the 2012 sailing events. By laying down as low as I could in the back end of our photo boat by the outboard motor in several inches of water and shooting at a wide open aperture I was able to create this effect. As the huge swell rose and fell and with waves lapping into our boat I felt lucky that the composition of the two 470 men's class boats was so symmetrically perfect and the glinting of the highlights in the water gave such a beautiful effect." - @clivejmason | August 4, 2012 [4 of 4] _ Getty Images sports photographer Clive Mason is taking over today for a behind the lens look at some of his favorite action shots. @gettyimages "This picture was captured whilst I was on assignment in Delhi covering a Formula 1 race. Having traveled to on numerous occasion for cricket tours and tournaments, I knew that India Gate was a great place to go in the late afternoon as lots of people, young and old alike, go there to partake in their favorite pastime. I set off one evening with my colleague (now my boss) @pgilham in a taxi hoping for a nice evening. I couldn't have been more pleased to find this youngster batting as his dad bowled at him. @gettyimages "This image is one that cemented my place on the team at back in 1995 and therefore remains another of my all time favorite photos. It features the cricket team playing a tour match on the beautiful Caribbean island of St. Kitts during their test series against the West Indies. I'd only been with the company for 10 months and was summoned to my boss' office and asked how I felt about covering in the Caribbean and naturally said I would be happy to do the shoot. The picture was shot shortly after a huge downpour and the clouds were moving across the skies quickly throwing areas into shade and bands of light were moving rapidly over the square. I exposed for the full light setting and ran up into the back of a stand and shot this frame. It was on transparency film so I didn't really know what I got until the films were couriered back to London and processed some weeks later. Suffice to say, it was a nice surprise when I walked back into the office and saw this frame." - @clivejmason | April 15, 1995 [2 of 4] _ Getty Images sports photographer Clive Mason is taking over today for a behind the lens look at some of his favorite action shots. When shooting one on one portraits with famous athletes or celebrities, you face many difficult factors - the most trying of which is the lack of time you have. After shooting football superstar before the 2014 FIFA in Brazil, I looked back on the time stamps and noticed that in the end I had only 38 seconds to cover a number of shots on a brief and then try to get something a little different. Normally players will give you a little more time, however he was running late for a team meeting and had to leave quickly. With the weight of a nation on his shoulders, and on the eve of leading Brazil into the worlds biggest sporting event in their own backyard, I wanted to portray the extreme confidence that Neymar portrays both on and off the field. I only took 12 frames in those 38 seconds, so to capture one with this much impact and feeling was very pleasing. - @ryanpierse | June 8, 2014 [3 of 3] __ Getty Images photographer Ryan Pierse is taking over @gettyimages today for a closer look at some of his favourite images. In a world where drone photography is becoming the norm, it is important to remember that some of the best quality aerial shots are still taken from helicopters. While hovering in a chopper above the famous Bondi Beach in Sydney, I captured this image of a swimmer being dwarfed by a rolling set of heavy surf. You want to minimize the amount of camera gear you take up in into the sky so by using a Canon 1DX Mark 2 and a Canon 100-400 lens, I was able to shoot many scenes at different focal lengths on the one camera. I love the texture and the power in this image and as moving water will never make exactly the same shape twice, this is a truly unique moment. - @ryanpierse | February 23, 2017 [2 of 3] __ Photographer Ryan Pierse is taking over @gettyimages today for a closer look at some of his favourite images. To see more of Ryans work check out his Instagram @ryanpierse __ The Olympic Games are the pinnacle for any Sports Photographer. The bread and butter of Sports photography is being able to freeze athletes at the absolute peak of their action. However, using certain photographic techniques, you can capture moments that are not visible to the human eye or a broadcast camera. Using an extremely slow shutter speed and a slight zoom burst technique, I shot this graphic image during the velodrome at the Rio Olympics. Years of practice and many many laps of patience on the day go into creating a image like this, so it was satisfying for everything to come together as such a major event. When your boss of 15 years comes over to you the next morning and asks you for a print of the image for his house, that can only be good thing. - @ryanpierse | August 16, 2016 [1 of 3]

@gettyimages I captured this image of the New Zealand All Black Sevens team after they won the final at the Hong Kong Rugby 7s in 2014. A typhoon hit Hong Kong and the rain was torrential. After they received the trophy the team took their jerseys off and performed a Haka in the downpour. I was down to one camera, the other was already water-damaged. The remember the moment as being spine-tingling. The other photographers had run for cover. I went out on the field and got down low in the wet grass that was starting to flood. The energy and raw emotion was a special moment to photograph and witness. One of the ongoing themes in my work, I hope, and one of the things I believe in, is a sense of human nature, a sense of shared humanity." - Chris Hondros (March 14, 1970 April 20, 2011) Paratroopers of the 82nd Airborne play touch football on the landing zone of a forward U.S. Army base in southeastern Afghanistan | October 5, 2002 _ Chris Hondros (March 14, 1970 April 20, 2011) was an American Pulitzer Prize-nominated photojournalist. He covered most of the world's major conflicts since the late 1990s, including wars in Kosovo, Angola, Sierra Leone, Lebanon, Afghanistan, Kashmir, the West Bank, Iraq, Liberia and Libya. He received dozens of awards, including the 2006 Robert Capa Gold Medal, war photography's highest honor, for his work in Iraq. Hondros was also a two-time Finalist for the Pulitzer Prize in Breaking News Photography for his work in Liberia in 2004 and his work on the Arab Spring in 2011. In addition to his photography, Hondros was a frequent lecturer and essayist on issues of war. Hondros was killed while on assignment in Misrata, Libya on April 20, 2011. @gettyimages is remembering Hondros' legacy by highlighting his work in his own words.

@gettyimages "This was my first ever commercial shoot and it was for . I shot it in Sydney and had to plan out everything, from the venue to the lighting. I got the gig as I could shoot and that was what the creative team wanted. I asked a few other photographers for some advice but remember I was still really nervous as there was a lot riding on the shoot. I used a light meter in a zip lock bag (really hi tech) to check exposure as I just loved the blues and colours you capture when shooting water. Everything came together after the two day shoot and it was still in the era of film so I sent back clip tests to the lab and waited nervously to see the results. I kind of miss that wait now that everyone is shooting digital." - @adampretty | 2002

@gettyimages "It was my first ever world swimming championships and my first time in . I couldnt sleep after the 24 hour flight for some reason, so I took a walk up the mountain to the diving venue. I had seen an awesome picture from Bob Martin from the Barcelona Olympics a few years earlier. The divers were training and I sat down and watched for a while. As the sun went lower I notice some birds flying up from the valley below heading home for the night and I got myself set up and waited. I sat there for a couple of hours and crossed my fingers that a diver would go off the board as a bird flew pass and after about 2 hours it happened. I remember all the other photographers had gone home except for one other and he was sitting about 20m down the stand from me. Just after it happened I nervously looked down at the screen on the back of the digital camera and my hands were shaking a little. I had a frame and I looked straight up to the other photographer and he was looking straight at me expectantly as well, and from his expression I could tell he didnt have it. It was one of those really fortunate moments where you see something and hope it is possible, and then everything comes together at the right time." - @adampretty | July 11, 2003

@gettyimages "It was the year before the Sydney which were going to be held in my hometown and I was absolutely pumped! I was given the assignment of photographing all the Olympic test events that would be held in the year before the Olympic Games. I was extremely fortunate to be exposed to sports I had never seen before, let alone photograph. I was also fortunate that my boss was pretty happy for me to go out and experiment as long as I came back with good information on each of the venues regarding photo positions, things that could be better, to try and make sure we got the best out of each venue when the real show was in town. It was the first time I had seen trampolining and it could not have been a better set up - a big black curtain covering half the venue which gave you an almost studio like set up. I wasnt able to bring a tripod into the venue so I had to lie down and keep the camera really steady on the ground. My slow shutter speed gave me a really nice movement effect on the athletes and the judges sitting motionless." - @adampretty | March 20, 1999
